data.jamchart_notes: Two main segments to this monster. Rick initially crafts a soaring hose motif as he and Peter really lock in on the dual guitars. As the first peak fades away, we are treated to a flamethrower of a ripping jam, going around for more and more builds before finally screaming into the finish. Winner of JOTY 2020.

data.jamchart_notes: Peter leans into the envelope filter on his guitar as the band luxuriates in an incredible funk zone for several minutes early on. Making a major-key push from there, Rick confidently leads several huge builds that come together for a massive final peak. Outstanding version.
Joyous, momentous build (you’ll know when it’s happening, impossible not to smile during it) that devolves into dark unregulated chaos before rising back in full fury finish.

data.jamchart_notes: Peter begins the jam with searing synth textures from his Nord Lead before switching to Vibe as a more melodic theme takes shape. The band fully explores this before bringing it home with a typically raging ending.

The "Madhuvanastasio." Peter initiates a descending "Mind Left Body"-like progression on marimba piano as Rick and Trey dance around each other's melodies. Trey takes the lead on a major-key space as the jam picks up speed. Peaking well, it deconstructs into a darker build with great interplay from the two guitars and keys before exploding home.

data.jamchart_notes: “DDS”/“The Doctor Will See You Now” vocal shenanigans lead to gorgeous bliss. Ben eventually hits double time and jam builds to soaring, beautiful first climax. In 16th minute, they return to traditional "Madhuvan" rocking. Peter takes lead with a few playful piano solos before Rick storms back in for an another blistering peak. Just when you think it may be winding down in minute 21, band rips back in and explodes the finish. One of the best jams, if not the best, of Euro Tour 23.

data.jamchart_notes: Jam begins from nothing as Rick begins to build a sinister motif. Peter lays down delayed Vibe as the rest of the band enters and gradually build into a beautifully evil churn. Rick then signals to Cotter at the apex and the drums drive forward into double-time, bringing us home in a blaze of glory to bookend this second set. Some really wild and articulate heavy metal builds from Rick.

data.jamchart_notes: Several mins of dissonance kicks off before Rick pulls the band into a funkier mode. Modulates to major and soars for a few mins - but the real work is just beginning. Digging into some evil tones with Peter laying on Vintage Vibe and then OB-6, the band builds into a massive black hole. Cotter pivots into a faster beat insinctively and Rick and Peter circle each other. Trevor blasts his way in just before the 26:00 with MASSIVE bombs before a "River Lullaby" jam develops and closes out this all-timer jam.

data.jamchart_notes: Two-guitar Goose reflects the first light of sunrise, its shamanic texture a tribute to the crisp dawn. The band patiently floats in that space before shifting into a frenetic and exploratory Ted-like jam. Returning to the song structure, Pete transitions to punctuated keys, inviting Rick into a cyclical step-jam typical of “Madhuvans.” With callbacks to the earlier “Mais Que Nada,” Rick builds to a deliberate peak, both provoked and matched by Trevor’s fierce, Cliff Burton-like bassline.

data.jamchart_notes: First of two behemoth versions from Winter '25. Two-guitar Goose at its FINEST. Rick and Peter get scratchy as Trevor leads Cotter into a heavy and dark space. From there, it's all-out pandemonium as the band moves from one menacing idea to the next, shifting and evolving through tones as the tension just builds and builds. Explodes into a peaky section as Cotter RELENTLESSLY pushes the pace through the finish.

The band goes HUGE on the encore for the second night in a row. Gets evil from the get-go with POUNDING Trevor and Cotter as Rick and Peter skip their usual spacey antics in favour of angular play. The tempo amps up and we are thrown headlong into Westville "Rockdale"-style space - edge-of-your-seat madness but with Peter on guitar. Trevor dials in synth effects as it gets crazier, the band setting their sights on the ending but getting there by way of several minutes of punishing darkness and wild sounds.

data.jamchart_notes: A pithier (if less adventurous) callback to the PNC “Madhuvan,” this version reprises the A/B sectional approach — oscillating between spacious exploration and heavier, almost metal segments. It dissolves quickly out of the head, with Trevor introducing a melodic idea that Rick runs with, before shifting into the familiar back-and-forth, patiently approaching its composed ending, and morphing seamlessly into “Atlas Dogs.”

data.jamchart_notes: Coming late in a show light on improv, Goose makes up for lost time with a twisted, dissonant section reminiscent of the Milwaukee and Grand Rapids versions from earlier in the year. From there, Rick executes a smooth modulation to a dreamy major key and Peter works in some subtle Rhodes textures as the bliss jam eventually winds its way home to a hot conclusion.

data.shownotes: Moby was played for the first time since February 13, 2025 (58 shows). Before the show, creepy music played and technical difficulties ensued marked by Loomis calling over the PA, suddenly the entire crowd was sent through the veil much like the 4 lads from the promo video. Upon landing in a new world Barnaby Glimpse welcomed his new friends to his Show Upon Time. Following his opening monologue, the band kicked into a Menagerie set marked by animal balloons, animal puppets and animal performers. Carnies also passed out Goose branded Animal Crackers. After Animal, Barnaby reappeared on stage for a brief monologue. During the encore, members slowly left the stage, Cotter first after Jed, then Stu and Trevor after Master & a Hound. Peter left during Sugar Mountain. At the end of the song, Rick shut off the lamp on his rig and left the stage.
